<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-06-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-06-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Dupuy de Lôme</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-06-24"><hi rend="italic">June 24,
                                1895</hi>.</date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 11.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In answer to a telegraphic dispatch from
                            this Department, the United States minister at Madrid wires that the
                            sensational articles in the Times and other New York papers, to which
                            you referred at our interview of the other day, are perfectly understood
                            in Madrid to be merely rumors, for which this Government is in no way
                            responsible.</p>
                        <p>Awaiting information respecting the answer to your telegram to Madrid, of
                            which you were good enough to apprise me, I take this opportunity,
                            etc.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard Olney.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>